'''John R. Sheehy''' (July 30, 1947) was a [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] member of the [[Illinois House of Representatives]] for a single term from 1993 to 1995. He represented the 37th district, which was located in [[Chicago Southland|Chicago's south suburbs]].<ref name="Blue Book">{{cite book|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|year=1994|title=Illinois Blue Book 1993-1994|url=http://www.idaillinois.org/cdm/ref/collection/bb/id/42794|location=[[Springfield, Illinois]]|publisher=[[Illinois Secretary of State]]|page=84|asin=B000FM19AI}}</ref> Born in [[Chicago, Illinois]]. Sheehy attended [[Moraine Valley Community College]] and graduated from Worsham College of Mortuary Science. After graduating from Worsham, he went to work for his father at Sheehy Funeral Homes. He is a veteran of the [[Vietnam War]].<ref name="Blue Book" /><ref name="1992 Primary" /> In 1992, Sheehy faced Carl James Vandenberg, who defeated fellow Republican and appointed incumbent Manny Hoffman of [[Homewood, Illinois|Homewood]].<ref name="1992 Primary">{{cite news|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1992-02-27/news/9201180756_1_midway-airlines-homewood-small-businesses|last=Tijerina|first=Edmond S.|title=House District 37 Has No Candidate Shortage|newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]]|location=[[Chicago, Illinois]]|date=February 27, 1992|accessdate=August 14, 2017}}</ref> Sheehy won the Republican leaning district by 239 votes.<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Wheeler III|first=Charles N.|date=October 1994|title='Home field' for GOP|url=http://www.lib.niu.edu/1994/ii941024.html|magazine=Illinois Issues|pages=25-26|location=[[Springfield, Illinois]]|publisher=[[Sangamon State University]]|access-date=August 14, 2017}}</ref> While a member of the Illinois House, he served on the following committees; Aging; Appropriations-Human Services; Elections & State Government; Elementary & Secondary Education; Registration & Regulation.<ref name="Blue Book" /> He was defeated for reelection by [[Ed Zabrocki]], the Mayor of [[Tinley Park, Illinois]], by 539 votes.<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Wheeler III|first=Charles N.|date=September 1995|title=A freshman lawmaker sends an early warning signal|url=http://www.lib.niu.edu/1995/ii950906.html|magazine=Illinois Issues|pages=6-7|location=[[Springfield, Illinois]]|publisher=[[Sangamon State University]]|access-date=August 14, 2017}}</ref>
