{{Other uses}}
[[Image:Destruction of Leviathan.png|right|250px|thumb|''The Destruction of [[Leviathan]]'' by [[Gustave Doré]] (1865)]]

'''Lotan''' ([[Ugaritic language|Ugaritic]]:&nbsp;𐎍𐎚𐎐''-ltn'', transliterated 
''Lôtān'',{{sfnp|Uehlinger|1999|p=514}} ''Litan'',{{sfnp|Barker|2014}} or ''Litānu'',{{sfnp|Herrmann|1999|p=133}} meaning "coiled") is a servant of the [[sea god]] [[Yam (god)|Yam]] defeated by the [[storm god]] [[Hadad|Hadad-Baʿal]] in the [[Ugaritic]] ''[[Baal Cycle]]''.{{sfnp|Herrmann|1999|p=133}} possibly with the help or by the hand of his sister [[ʿAnat]].{{sfnp|Baumgarten|1981|p=[https://books.google.com.hk/books?id=BM8UAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA208 208]}} 
Lotan seems to have been prefigured by the serpent ''Têmtum'' represented in Syrian seals of the 18th–16th century BC, {{sfnp|Uehlinger|1999|p=512}} and finds a later reflex in the sea monster ''[[Leviathan]]'', whose defeat at the hands of [[Yahweh]] is alluded to in the [[Hebrew Bible|biblical]] [[Book of Job]] and in [[Book of Isaiah|Isaiah]] 27:1.{{sfnp|Uehlinger|1999|p=512}}{{sfnp|Herrmann|1999|p=133}} 
Lambert (2003) went as far as the claim that [[Book of Isaiah|Isaiah]] 27:1 is a direct quote lifted from the Ugaritic text, correctly rendering Ugaritic ''bṯn'' "snake" as Hebrew ''nḥš'' "snake".<ref>W.G. Lambert, "Leviathan in Ancient Art" in ''FS Shlomo Moussaieff'' (ed. R. Deutsch), 2003, 147&ndash;154 (p. 154)</ref>{{sfnp|Barker|2014|p=[https://books.google.com.hk/books?id=cXRZJlN8BbwC&pg=PA152 152]}}

''Lotan'' (''ltn'') is an adjectival formation meaning "coiled", here used as a proper name;{{sfnp|Baumgarten|1981|p=[https://books.google.com.hk/books?id=BM8UAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA208 208]}} the same creature has a number of possible epitheta, including  "the fugitive serpent" (''bṯn brḥ'') and maybe (with some uncertainty deriving from manuscript lacunae) "the wriggling serpent" (''bṯn ʿqltn'') and "the mighty one with seven heads" (''šlyṭ d.šbʿt rašm'').{{sfnp|Uehlinger|1999|p=512}}

The myth of Hadad defeating Lotan, Yahweh defeating Leviathan, Marduk defeating Tiamat (etc.) in the mythologies of the Ancient Near East are classical examples of the ''[[Chaoskampf]]'' mytheme, also reflected in [[Zeus]]' slaying of [[Typhon]] in [[Greek mythology]]{{sfnp|Ogden|2013}} and [[Thor]]'s struggle against [[Jörmungandr]] in the [[Gylfaginning]] portion of the [[Prose Edda]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Prose Edda|last=Sturluson|first=Snorri|publisher=[[Penguin Classics]]|year=2005|isbn=|location=London|pages=}}</ref>

