'''Práxedes Fajardo y Puno''' (21 July 1874 – 10 August 1928) was a [[Philippine]] revolutionary and head of the [[Pampanga]]n section of the [[Philippine Red Cross]] during the anticolonial armed struggles against [[Philippine Revolution|Spain]] and the [[Philippine–American War|United States]].
Fajardo was born in [[Bacolor, Pampanga|Bacólor]] to Justino Fajardo and Andrea Puno. Educated at [[La Consolacion College Manila|La Consolación]] in [[Manila]], she would later be known for her organizational acumen as head of the Philippine Red Cross in Pampanga.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cityofsanfernando.gov.ph/forvisitors/localheroes/praxedesfajardo|title=Praxedes Fajardo - Local Hero|first=Management Information Technology Division|last=(MITD)|website=City of San Fernando - Christmas Capital of the Philippines|accessdate=14 September 2018}}</ref> She had been sent along with [[Nicolasa Dayrit Panlilio]] to mediate between generals [[Antonio Luna]] and [[Tomás Mascardo]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/931341/anonymous-no-more-woman-hero-of-revolution-vs-us|title=Anonymous no more: Woman hero of revolution vs US|newspaper=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]]|accessdate=14 September 2018}}</ref>
Fajardo remained unmarried throughout her life, instead opting to take care of her sister Florencia Gutiérrez’ family.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pinoyfolktales.blogspot.com/2013/01/filipino-martyr-praxedes-p-fajardo.html|title=Pinoy Folk Tales: Filipino Martyr: PRAXEDES P. FAJARDO|first=|last=Den|date=18 January 2013|website=Pinoyfolktales.blogspot.com|accessdate=14 September 2018}}</ref>
