{{Infobox playwright |name=R. C. Sherriff |image=R. C. Sherriff.jpg |caption= |birth_name=Robert Cedric Sherriff |birth_date={{Birth date|1896|6|6|df=y}} |birth_place=[[Hampton Wick]], [[Middlesex]], England |death_date={{Death date and age|1975|11|13|1896|6|6|df=y}} |death_place=[[Kingston upon Thames]], England |occupation=[[Playwright]] and [[screenwriter]] |nationality=British |magnum_opus= Stage: [[Journey's End]]; Film: [[The Dam Busters (film)|The Dam Busters]] |period=1920s to 1960s |partner= |children= |relatives= |influences= |influenced= |awards= |signature= |website= |portaldisp=}} '''Robert Cedric Sherriff''', [[Fellow of the Society of Antiquaries|FSA]], [[Fellow of the Royal Society of Literature|FRSL]] (6 June 1896 – 13 November 1975)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ibdb.com/broadway-cast-staff/r-c-sherriff-8204|title=R. C. Sherriff – Broadway Cast & Staff - IBDB|first=The Broadway|last=League|website=www.ibdb.com}}</ref> was an [[English people|English]] writer best known for his play ''[[Journey's End]]'',<ref name="Stevens">{{cite book |last= Stevens |first= Christopher |title= Born Brilliant: The Life Of Kenneth Williams |publisher= John Murray |year= 2010 |isbn = 1-84854-195-3 |page=264 }}</ref> which was based on his experiences as an army officer in the First World War.<ref name=britannica/> He wrote several plays, novels, and screenplays, and was nominated for an [[Academy Award for Best Adapted Screenplay|Academy Award]] and two [[British Academy of Film and Television Arts|BAFTA awards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archiveshub.jisc.ac.uk/data/gb176-2332|title=R C SHERRIFF (1896-1975), DRAMATIST AND NOVELIST: CORRESPONDENCE AND PAPERS - Archives Hub|publisher=}}</ref>
==Early life== Sherriff was born in [[Hampton Wick]], [[Middlesex]], to insurance clerk Herbert Hankin Sherriff and Constance Winder.<ref name="ukpro"/> He was educated at [[Kingston Grammar School]] in [[Kingston upon Thames]] from 1905-1913.{{#tag:ref| Sherriff maintained close links with the school for the rest of his life. He sent a copy of ''Journey's End'' to the headmaster after the play was first performed in 1928, and was a generous benefactor to the school until his death, paying particularly close attention to the school rowing club, whose supporters' club now bears his name. He financed a number of boats named after his plays (''Journey's End'', ''White Carnation'', ''Home at Seven'', ''Long Sunset'' and ''Badger's Green''). He also purchased a piece of land at the end of Aragon Avenue in [[Thames Ditton]] for the purpose of building a school boathouse,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sherriffclub.org/boathousehistory.html|title=Boathouse history|publisher=KGS Sherriff Club|accessdate=19 September 2015}}</ref> which was completed in 1980. |group= n}}
After he left school, Sherriff worked in an [[insurance]] office as a clerk (from 1914) and as an insurance adjuster (1918 to 1928) at [[Sun Life Financial|Sun Insurance Company]], London.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.twickenham-museum.org.uk/detail.php?aid=310&cid=7&ctid=1|title=Twickenham Museum - R C Sherriff|website=www.twickenham-museum.org.uk}}</ref> Sherriff served as an officer in the 9th battalion of the [[East Surrey Regiment]] in the [[World War I|First World War]], taking part in the fighting at [[Battle of Vimy Ridge|Vimy Ridge]] and [[battle of Loos|Loos]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.express.co.uk/expressyourself/259375/Sadness-that-forever-lies-at-Journey-s-End|title=Sadness that forever lies at Journey’s End|first=Jane|last=Clinton|date=17 July 2011|publisher=}}</ref> He was severely wounded at [[Passendale|Passchendaele]] near [[Ypres]] in 1917.<ref name="sherriff1968pp14,22" />
Sherriff studied at [[New College, Oxford]] from 1931 to 1934.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.exploringsurreyspast.org.uk/themes/people/writers/sherriff/|title=RC Sherriff (1896 - 1975) - Exploring Surrey's Past|website=www.exploringsurreyspast.org.uk}}</ref> He was a fellow of the [[Royal Society of Literature]] and the [[Society of Antiquaries of London]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hwremembers.org.uk/rcsherriff/rcsherriff.php|title=HWR|website=www.hwremembers.org.uk}}</ref>
==Career==
===Playwright=== He first wrote a play to help [[Kingston Rowing Club]] raise money to buy a new boat.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.exploringsurreyspast.org.uk/sherriff-blog-11/|title=The road to Journey’s End...A Hitch in the Proceedings and other early plays by R C Sherriff - Exploring Surrey's Past|website=www.exploringsurreyspast.org.uk}}</ref> His seventh play, ''[[Journey's End]]'', was written in 1928 and published in 1929 and was based on his experiences in the war.<ref name=britannica>{{cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/biography/R-C-Sherriff|title=R.C. Sherriff - British writer|publisher=}}</ref> It was given a single Sunday performance, on 9 December 1928, by the [[Incorporated Stage Society]] at the [[Apollo Theatre]], directed by [[James Whale]] and with the 21-year-old [[Laurence Olivier]] in the lead role.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://theatricalia.com/play/30f/journeys-end/production/mj4|title=Production of Journey’s End - Theatricalia|website=theatricalia.com}}</ref> In the audience was [[Maurice Browne]] who produced it at the [[Savoy Theatre]] where it was performed for two years from 1929.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://theatricalia.com/play/30f/journeys-end/production/6rw|title=Production of Journey’s End - Theatricalia|website=theatricalia.com}}</ref>
===Novelist=== Sherriff also wrote prose. A novelised version of ''Journey's End'', co-written with [[Vernon Bartlett]], was published in 1930.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=CKUhAQAAIAAJ&pg=RA1-PA452&lpg=RA1-PA452&dq=Journey's+End+novel+r.c.+sherriff+with+Vernon+Bartlett+published+in+1930&source=bl&ots=QzRCgFowHL&sig=YhL6fGr7frLdr_ft_AJh2unNNzk&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi45fnkkb_XAhVjJsAKHeTpAu8Q6AEIYDAO#v=onepage&q=Journey's+End+novel+r.c.+sherriff+with+Vernon+Bartlett+published+in+1930&f=false|title=Catalog of Copyright Entries. New Series: 1930|date=14 November 2017|publisher=Copyright Office, Library of Congress|via=Google Books}}</ref> His 1939 novel, ''[[The Hopkins Manuscript]]'' is an [[H. G. Wells]]-influenced post-apocalyptic story about an earth devastated because of a collision with the Moon.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/books/bookreviews/6133642/Endpaper.html|title=Endpaper|first=Claudia|last=FitzHerbert|date=5 September 2009|publisher=|via=www.telegraph.co.uk}}</ref> Its sober language and realistic depiction of an average man coming to terms with a ruined England is said{{citation needed|date=February 2018}} to have been an influence on later science fiction authors such as [[John Wyndham]] and [[Brian Aldiss]]. ''The Fortnight in September'', an earlier novel, published in 1931, is a rather more plausible story about a [[Bognor Regis|Bognor]] holiday enjoyed by a lower-middle-class family from [[Dulwich]].<ref>http://www.persephonebooks.co.uk/the-fortnight-in-september.html</ref> His 1936 novel ''Green Gates'' is a realistic novel about a middle-aged couple, Tom and Edith Baldwin, moving from an established London suburb into the then-new suburbs of [[Metro-land]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bookssnob.wordpress.com/2016/12/03/greengates-by-r-c-sherriff/|title=Greengates by R C Sherriff|date=3 December 2016|publisher=}}</ref>
==Award nominations== Sherriff was nominated along with [[Eric Maschwitz]] and [[Claudine West]] for an [[Academy Award for Best Adapted Screenplay|Academy award for writing an adapted screenplay]] for ''[[Goodbye, Mr. Chips (1939 film)|Goodbye, Mr. Chips]]'' which was released in 1939.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmovie.com/artist/rc-sherriff-p164845/awards|title=R.C. Sherriff - Movie and Film Awards - AllMovie|website=AllMovie}}</ref> His 1955 screenplays, ''[[The Dam Busters (film)|The Dam Busters]]'' and ''[[The Night My Number Came Up]]'' were nominated for best British screenplay [[British Academy of Film and Television Arts|BAFTA award]]s.<ref name="glancy2008" />
