{{italic title}} {{EngvarB|date=September 2015}} {{Use dmy dates|date=September 2015}}
'''''Wee Peem''''' ("He's a Proper Scream") was a British comic strip, created by James Jewell.<ref name=A>{{cite book | title=The History of the Beano|publisher=D.C. Thomson & Co. Ltd.|location=Dundee, Scotland |year=2008 |pages= 305|isbn=978-1-902407-73-9}}</ref> It ran in ''[[The Beano]]'' from 1938 on and ceased publication in 1957.
==History== The series was first published in the first issue of the comic book magazine ''[[The Beano]]'' , dated July 30, 1938, and ran until the 89th issue, dated April 6, 1940. This first incarnation also appeared in the 1940 and 1941 [[The Beano Book|Beano Books]].
The central character "Wee Peem" was a young boy who gets up to various forms of mischief in a similar way to later Beano strips such as [[Dennis the Menace (UK)|Dennis the Menace]] and [[Minnie the Minx]]. The name "Peem" is commonly a diminutive form of "James" in North East Scotland.
==Publication history== These first Wee Peem strips were later reprinted in [[D. C. Thomson & Co. Ltd|D.C. Thomson]]'s magazine-cum-newspaper [[The People's Journal]] which were followed by new Wee Peem strips in [[The People's Journal]] this time drawn by James Malcolm.<ref name=A/> The character then reappeared in issue 486, dated 10 November 1951, this time drawn by Charles Grigg, in a new strip entitled ''Wee Peem's Magic Pills''<ref name=B>{{cite book | title=The History of the Beano|publisher=D.C. Thomson & Co. Ltd.|location=Dundee, Scotland |year=2008 |pages= 317|isbn=978-1-902407-73-9}}</ref> in this new strip the character was redesigned to have a massive head and took pills which gave him magic powers. This new strip lasted until issue 507, dated 5 April 1952, and appeared in the 1953 Beano Book.<ref name=B/> The character then reappeared for a third and final time in 1956 in a new strip this time simply entitled Wee Peem.<ref name=C>{{cite book | title=The History of the Beano|publisher=D.C. Thomson & Co. Ltd.|location=Dundee, Scotland |year=2008 |pages= 323|isbn=978-1-902407-73-9}}</ref> In this final Wee Peem strip, drawn by Hugh Morren, the character was redesigned yet again and this final Wee Peem comic strip lasted until 1957.<ref name=C/>
==Dipper the Dodger==
A similar character in both appearance and mannerisms appeared in the first [[Dandy Monster Comic]] under the name Dipper the Dodger.<ref name=DMC1>{{cite book | title=Dandy Monster Comic No. 1|publisher=D.C. Thomson & Co. Ltd. in conjunction with Aurum Press Ltd.|location=Dundee, Scotland |year=2006 |pages= 54,86,127|isbn=1-84513-217-3}}</ref>
